message.content:
A 'dowitcher' is a type of sandpiper bird found in North America. 
They have a long, curved and thin bill that helps them feed on insects, crustaceans and small mollusks. 
Their plumage is variable, from rufous-brown to grey-brown, with streaks, spots or bars of darker color. 
Their wingspan is about 50-60 cm and they weigh around 70-100 grams. 
During breeding season, males exhibit more contrasting and brighter colors than females. 
They are commonly found in coastal wetlands, mudflats, estuaries and marshes, where they forage and rest in flocks. 
In migratory season, they may fly in large numbers towards South America as far as Argentina.
